          "body": "The fifth petition (6:32-33) breaks the pattern of Israel's crises to include the *nokhri*, the foreigner who is 'not from Your people Israel.' This foreigner comes 'from a far country for Your great name's sake and Your mighty hand and Your outstretched arm' — the Exodus language applied to a non-Israelite. Solomon's stated purpose for hearing this foreigner's prayer is explicitly missiological: 'that all the peoples of the earth may know Your name, and fear You as do Your people Israel, and that they may know that this house which I have built is called by Your name' (6:33). The Temple is not an ethnic monument. It is the locus of God's self-revelation to the nations. This petition anticipates Isaiah 56:7, which Jesus quotes in Mark 11:17 — 'My house shall be called a house of prayer for all the peoples.' The New Testament's application of Temple-language to the church (1 Corinthians 3:16; Ephesians 2:21-22) and to Christ Himself (John 2:19-21) stands in direct continuity with Solomon's own vision."
